Subject: EVDI CPU-buffer capture backend (display_evdi_t) + libevdi event pump + cleanup

This is the patch that finally makes Apollo's stream show the *virtual* desktop
content instead of either mirroring the physical monitor or crashing on the
EVDI card.

## The architectural problem patches 0005 + 0006 (archived) couldn't solve

Apollo's existing KMS capture pipeline (kmsgrab.cpp display_ram_t /
display_vram_t) is built around real GPU framebuffers:
   open(/dev/dri/cardN) -> gbm_create_device(fd) -> eglCreateImage(dma-buf)
   -> glGetTextureSubImage -> img->data
That entire chain assumes the card is a GPU with DRI/render support. An EVDI
card has no render node and isn't a real GPU — `gbm_create_device` on it
SIGSEGVs inside libgallium's `driCreateNewScreen3` (graphify graph confirms
the crash site as `display_ram_t::init`).

Patches 0005 + 0006 tried to make EVDI work through that same pipeline.
0005 added the libevdi event pump (register_buffer / request_update /
handle_events / grab_pixels) so kwin's pageflips would complete. 0006 cleaned
up stale `/dev/dri/cardN` between runs. Both fixed real bugs but they kept
Apollo on the GBM/EGL path, and that path is what crashes mesa.

## The fix

Build a parallel capture lane that NEVER touches the EVDI card via mesa:

  display_evdi_t (this patch) ----- evdi_grab_pixels ----- AMD GPU (va_ram_t)
  ^                                                       ^
  reads CPU buffer that libevdi      uploads CPU pixels to a VA surface using
  fills from kwin's pageflips        /dev/dri/renderD128 (the AMD render node)

Apollo already has a CPU-pixels-in lane: `va::make_avcodec_encode_device(w, h,
vram=false)` returns `va_ram_t`, which calls `egl::sws_t::load_ram` to upload
host BGRA8888 onto a VA surface. We reuse that lane unchanged.

The graphify graph surfaced the critical bridge:

   va_ram_t  --semantically_similar_to-->  struct evdi_buffer (CPU pixel buffer)
   copy_primary_pixels (kernel memcpy) -- semantically_similar_to --> display_ram_t::snapshot

i.e. the data shapes already match (BGRA8888 packed, width*4 stride). The
EVDI driver's mode_changed notification confirms `AR24 little-endian` = BGRA
in memory.

## Components

1. **VDISPLAY::EvdiBuffer** (virtual_display.h) — a thread-safe CPU pixel
   buffer with `copy_to(dst, stride)` for readers and `mark_updated()` for
   the event pump. shared_ptr-managed so the capture side can outlive a
   removeVirtualDisplay race.

2. **VDISPLAY::getEvdiBuffer(name)** — name-keyed lookup. Returns the
   shared_ptr for "VIRTUAL-XXXX" display names, nullptr otherwise.

3. **evdi_events_loop** (virtual_display.cpp) — single global thread that
   polls every active EVDI handle's event fd, dispatches `evdi_handle_events`,
   calls `evdi_grab_pixels` (the ioctl that releases the kernel's queued
   vblank), bumps the buffer's frame_number, re-arms `evdi_request_update`.
   2ms tick = under half a 240Hz frame, low CPU.

4. **cleanup_stale_evdi_devices** (virtual_display.cpp) — writes "1" to
   /sys/devices/evdi/remove_all on driver open AND close. Otherwise a
   leftover EVDI card from a crashed prior run would be picked up by Apollo's
   startup KMS probe and crash gbm_create_device.

5. **display_evdi_t** (kmsgrab.cpp) — the new capture class. Inherits from
   platf::display_t directly (NOT kms::display_t — we don't want any of the
   GBM/EGL setup). init() looks up the EvdiBuffer, capture()/snapshot loop
   memcpys it into img_out->data. make_avcodec_encode_device returns va_ram_t.
   alloc_img returns a kms_img_t with a CPU heap buffer.

6. **kms_display() factory** (kmsgrab.cpp) — checks for "VIRTUAL-" prefix in
   display_name and instantiates display_evdi_t. Falls through to the
   existing display_ram_t / display_vram_t path on failure or for non-virtual
   displays, so streaming the physical monitor still works exactly as before.

7. **kms_display_names() startup probe** (kmsgrab.cpp) — skips any /dev/dri/cardN
   whose `device/driver` symlink points at `evdi`. Defense against stale
   cards bypassing cleanup_stale_evdi_devices (e.g. if a non-Apollo process
   created an EVDI card).

## End-to-end flow

1. Steam Deck connects -> session manager calls VDISPLAY::createVirtualDisplay
   -> patch 1's fixed find_available_evdi_device, patch 3's no-spurious-open,
   patch 2's kscreen promote.
2. createVirtualDisplay now ALSO allocates an EvdiBuffer (width*height*4
   bytes), calls evdi_register_buffer + evdi_request_update.
3. Patch 4 lets kwin enumerate the new DRM connector. kwin starts rendering.
4. Every kwin pageflip queues a vblank in the kernel. The evdi_events_loop
   thread polls, dispatches, calls grab_pixels -> kernel copies the rendered
   GBM buffer into our EvdiBuffer -> releases the queued vblank -> kwin's
   pageflip completes -> kwin draws the next frame. (No more "Pageflip timed
   out!" spam.)
5. Apollo's video session calls kms_display(VIRTUAL-XXXX) -> the factory
   returns display_evdi_t (no GBM, no crash).
6. display_evdi_t::capture loop pulls an empty img from the pool, copy_to's
   the EvdiBuffer into img->data, pushes it to the encoder.
7. va_ram_t uploads the BGRA bytes via egl::sws_t::load_ram onto a VA surface
   on the AMD GPU (renderD128), the VAAPI encoder produces H264/HEVC/AV1,
   moonlight on the Steam Deck shows the virtual desktop.

## What's NOT in this patch

- xdg-desktop-portal / PipeWire screencast. Would be the "cleanest" architecture
  but requires substantial new code in Apollo and isn't necessary.
- Cursor compositing. kwin renders the cursor into the framebuffer that EVDI
  shadows, so it shows up naturally. display_evdi_t ignores the `cursor` flag.

